		<body>
			<pb n="1R"/>
				<p rend="The following 5 lines printed as a letterhead&#44; April 19th inserted on dotted line."></p>
				<p rend="align(center)">Office Assistant Quartermaster&#44;</p>
			<p rend="align(center)"><placeName>Bureau Refugees&#44; Freedmen and Abandoned Lands</placeName>&#44;</p>
			<p rend="align(center)"><placeName>STATE OF LOUISIANA</placeName></p>
			<p rend="align(center)"><placeName>No. 32 Carondelet St.</placeName></p>
			<p rend="align(center)"><placeName>New Orleans</placeName> <date>April 19th 1866</date></p>
			<p rend="align(center)"><addressee>Revd Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">My dear Sir&#44;</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Your favor under date <date>12</date> Inst. is before<lb/> me&#44; &#38; felt some what <sic>supprised</sic> to find you have<lb/> sent the Books by Express without my ordering<lb/> them&#44; If you will <sic>refere</sic> to my letter on the<lb/> subject you will find I only asked if you Could<lb/> Supply me with a set of the same as I had of<lb/> you some time ago.  &#38; what would be the price<lb/> if sent by the Express.  I called at the express office<lb/> &#38; found the parcel but in my asking to open it<lb/> the refused until I paid &#36;73.40<lb/>100 which I refused<lb/> to do until I heard from you on the subject.<lb/>  You may remember I only paid you &#36;3<add>&#63;</add> in paper &#38; I had them bound in Red Morocco &#38; Gold with<lb/> my name which cost &#36;12 in <placeName>New York</placeName> making them to<lb/> cost &#36;48 only.  Yet I suppose as labour is now<lb/> higher &#38; things altered I must submit to a higher<lb/> price.  I am sorry you are so <sic>premiture</sic> in<lb/> sending them until they were ordered.  I find</p>
			<pb n="1V"/>
				<p>you charge &#36;25 for five Vol &#38; &#36;37 for seven<lb/> why a <sic>diffeer</sic> of &#36;2 on the Seven&#63;  I want<lb/> the Books and will have no objections<lb/> to pay the part of the Bill&#44; say &#36;68.40<lb/>100 but<lb/> I will not pay one Cent more&#44; as I consider<lb/> that amount quite enough&#44;&#61; you will therefore<lb/> have to send a note enclosed in my letter<lb/> to the Express office directing them to allow me to inspect the Books before I pay<lb/> the amount and if they are to orders<lb/> of my memorandum<add>&#63;</add> say Bound in <sic>Morrocco</sic><lb/> &#38; Gold Gilt Edges and names on the covers<lb/> I will pay the amnt. but I shall never consent<lb/> to pay such exorbitant charges&#61; if you were<lb/> not so <sic>premiture</sic> I intended to have got them<lb/> sent to <placeName>New York</placeName> to a friend who would have brought them free of charge.  Besides you<lb/> have not stated what books you sent &#38;<lb/> if all my memorandum calls for&#44; are sent&#44;<lb/> please look on my Memorandum as I named<lb/> all the Books I wanted&#44;  times are very<lb/> hard and you must <add>not</add> blame me if I seek<lb/> to get what I want&#44; please let me hear from<lb/> you <sic>imediately</sic> as I wish to have this matter<lb/> closed one way or the other&#44; as it is no use<lb/> having the books laying at the Express office.<lb/>  Remember&#44; send the letter to allow me to look at them<lb/> &#38; I am to pay <hi rend="underline">only</hi> the nett amnt of &#36;68.40<lb/> &#38; no more for <sic>chages</sic>&#59; if they are to my <add>&#63;</add><lb/> trusting to hear from you <sic>imediately</sic>  I am</p>
			<p rend="indent(5)">Yours <sic>Respetfully</sic></p>
			<p rend="indent(5)"><persName role="author">D. Carvalho</persName></p>
		</body>
